<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<book>
    <page>
        <scene id="test">
            <root visible="true">
                <rotation y="90"/>
            </root>
            <model id="cat1" path="Persian.glb">
                <scale xyz="0.1"/>
                <position x="-1" z="-1"/>
            </model>
            <model id="cat2" path="Persian.glb">
                <scale xyz="0.1"/>
                <position xz="1"/>
                <rotation y="90"/>
            </model>
            <model id="spiderbot1" path="spiderbot.glb">
                <scale xyz="0.2"/>
            </model>
            <model id="spiderbot2" path="spiderbot.glb">
                <scale xyz="0.2"/>
                <position x="-1" z="1"/>
            </model>
            <model id="predator" path="Predator_s.glb">
                <scale xyz="0.3"/>
                <position x="1"/>
            </model>
            <action id="hide cats">
                <changeVisibility target="cat1" visible="false"/>
                <changeVisibility target="cat2" visible="false"/>
            </action>
            <action id="show cats">
                <changeVisibility target="cat1" visible="true"/>
                <changeVisibility target="cat2" visible="true"/>
            </action>
            <action id="move predator">
                <changePosition target="predator" x="0.1" z="0.2"/>
            </action>
        </scene>
        <content>
            Once when I was six years old I saw a magnificent picture in a book, called True
            Stories from Nature, about the primeval forest. It was a picture of a boa constrictor
            in the act of swallowing an animal. Here is a copy of the drawing.
            In the book it said: "Boa constrictors swallow their prey <keyword action="hide cats">whole</keyword>, without chewing
            it. After that they are not able to move, and they sleep through the six months that
            they need for digestion."
        </content>
    </page>
</book>